Ultrasound (USG) is the first-line, non-invasive, and accessible investigation to assess for biliary atresia, particularly identifying features like a hypoplastic or absent gallbladder and the triangular cord sign. While its diagnostic accuracy is approximately 78%, it remains the preferred initial screening tool due to cost-effectiveness and safety in neonates. More accurate modalities like hepatobiliary scintigraphy or MRCP are reserved for equivocal cases or when ultrasound fails to clarify the diagnosis.

